ger. Remove hash_re entirely or restrict it to a clearly PR-context pattern to prevent the review loop from targeting the wrong PR."},{"file":".claude/scripts/implement-issue-orchestrator.sh","line":975,"severity":"major","description":"grep -oE '\\[[ ]*\\{[^]]+\\]' uses [^]]+ which stops at the first ']' character, silently truncating any task object that contains a nested array (e.g. a 'dependencies' field). The subsequent jq validation then fails and nothing is extracted. Given the orchestrator's own task schemas include nested arrays (see lines 347-358), this will commonly produce no output for real payloads. Replace with a balanced-bracket parser (e.g. a small python3 -c snippet) or explicitly document the limitation."},{"file":".claude/scripts/implement-issue-test/test-stage-runner.bats","line":162,"severity":"minor","description":"No negative test verifies that a result text containing a bare '#N' reference (e.g. 'Implemented issue #52') does NOT set pr_number. This is the exact scenario that would catch the hash_re false-positive bug. Add a test: result text contains '#52' in an issue-reference context and assert pr_number is empty/null in the fallback output."},{"file":".claude/scripts/implement-issue-test/test-stage-runner.bats","line":173,"severity":"minor","description":"New timeout() mocks do not call 'shift' to skip the timeout argument, unlike the reference test '@test run_stage extracts structured_output' which does. Functionally harmless since mock bodies ignore all args, but inconsistent with the established convention in the test file."}],"comments":"What was done well: the recovery block is logically sound, jq mutation chaining is injection-safe (pr_num comes from a [0-9]+ capture), the four new bats tests cover the main happy-path scenarios consistently with the existing test patterns, and the feature addresses a real reliability gap. Fixes needed before this task can be considered complete: remove or tighten hash_re (major), fix the tasks array